Han Bo and Lin Qiu nodded fiercely, their gazes fixed on Liang with something like reverence. To them, he had been more than a comrade. He had been the wall itself.
But not all eyes were admiring.
From the inner disciples’ gallery, voices whispered sharp as knives.
“Reckless brute.”
“He bleeds like an animal.”
“Without Chen Rui, none would have returned.”
Chen Rui accepted their praise with a calm smile, his hands folded neatly, every inch the picture of grace. His gaze slid to Liang, faint amusement curling his lips.
Liang ignored it. He had no need for words. His body, torn and bloodied yet unbroken, spoke more loudly than any whisper.
By dawn, the squad was summoned to the Hall of Assembly. The elders sat in their high seats, lamplight gleaming off their solemn faces.
Elder Jian spoke first, his voice rumbling like stone. “The mission succeeded. The outpost stands. Yet again, the beasts press closer, and yet again, the Wall groans.” His staff struck the floor once, sparks leaping. “This is no ordinary season.”
Elder Yun’s gaze cut to Liang. “Reports speak of his recklessness. Blood spent needlessly, wounds taken in place of skill. He does not fight with refinement. He endures, yes but endurance without wisdom is a rope fraying with every pull.”
