Liang bowed, breath steady. “Yes, Elder.”
The chain tightened further but so too did his resolve.
By midday, the sect buzzed with news. Disciples gathered in clusters, excitement and tension sparking like fire.
“An open tournament?”
“Finally, we’ll see if Liang is more than scars.”
“Inner disciples will crush him.”
“Unless he crushes them first.”
Outer disciples rallied around him, their voices fierce. “He stood for us. He bled for us. Let the inners test him he’ll endure.”
Inners sneered openly. “A provisional mutt in a lion’s ring. He won’t last three rounds.”
Lines were being drawn, not by elders alone but by disciples themselves. The sect, once fractured quietly, now split openly outers with Liang, inners against him.
That evening, as Liang trained on the upper terraces, Mei Lin approached. Her expression was guarded, her steps measured.
“You’ve stirred the sect,” she said quietly. “Half call you hero, half call you fool. Do you understand what this tournament means?”
Liang exhaled, breath slow, stance steady. “It means I fight.”
“It means more than that,” she pressed. “It means every eye will be upon you. Elders, disciples, even the Wall itself. If you falter, the outers’ hope falters with you. If you win… you’ll make enemies who will not forget it.”
Liang straightened, wiping sweat from his brow. “I’ve carried worse weights.”
She studied him, lips parting as though to say more, but she only shook her head. “Be careful, Liang. Some victories cut deeper than defeats.”
She turned and left. Liang returned to his forms, the mountain mist curling around him like unseen pressure.
Far from the terraces, Ren Yao trained alone in a dark grotto. His blade blurred unnaturally, fissures glowing faintly under his skin. The seed pulsed in his chest, whispering eagerly.
A tournament. The perfect stage. Let him stand before the sect. Let them cheer. And then let them see you break him.
Ren’s grin was sharp, eyes glinting in the dark. “Yes. I’ll crush him where all can see. His endurance will mean nothing against brilliance.”
The fissures along his arms pulsed, and the shadow’s laughter echoed faintly through the grotto.
Back in his quarters, Liang sat cross legged, jade token resting in his palm. The sparrow perched on the window, feathers glinting in starlight.
The sect had set the stage. Recognition would not be given quietly it would be fought for, earned in blood, and weighed against resentment sharpened to blades.
Liang closed his eyes, breath sinking deep.
Then let them come.
 
Chapter 31: Factions Forming
The sect was no longer quiet.
