Fen’s eyes narrowed. “Then break him. Show the sect what brilliance looks like next to stubbornness.”
Rui’s smile was cold. “Not brilliance. Precision. We need not kill him only show his endurance for the brute’s trick it is. The crowd will see. The elders will see. His fall will be swift.”
Mei Rong said nothing, though her eyes lingered on the courtyard where Liang trained. Her silence was unreadable, her thoughts her own.
In a grotto beneath the mountain, Ren Yao trained alone. His blade blurred unnaturally fast, fissures glowing faint beneath his skin. The seed pulsed with every breath, its whispers intoxicating.
A tournament, it coiled. The perfect stage. Let them cheer for him. Let their hope rise. And then let them watch you shatter it. Their cheers will turn to fear, their faith to silence.
Ren laughed softly, his breath sharp. “Yes. I’ll break him before all eyes. He’ll regret ever stepping beyond the outers.”
The fissures spread faintly across his arm, and the shadow within purred with delight.
That evening, Elder Shen summoned Liang to his study. The room was filled with the scent of ink and parchment, scrolls stacked neatly against the walls. Shen sat cross-legged, his eyes calm but piercing.
“You feel the weight,” Shen said without preamble. “The sect does not whisper lightly.”
Liang bowed. “Yes, Elder.”
“Do not mistake their voices for truth,” Shen continued. “The sect is fractured. Some will cheer your rise, others will sharpen blades against it. The tournament will not only test your strength it will test your heart.”
Liang straightened, breath steady. “Then I will endure.”
Shen’s lips curved faintly. “Endurance has carried you far. But remember endurance is not only for your body. It is for your will. When the crowd jeers, when rivals sneer, when shadows tempt you endure then most of all.”
Liang bowed deeply. “I will remember.”
As Liang left the study, the sparrow swooped down, landing briefly on the railing. Its black eyes glinted, feathers ruffling in the wind.
The sect was no longer quiet.
It was a storm gathering, factions forming, and all eyes would soon be fixed on the dueling platform.
Liang clenched his fists, breath sinking deep.
Then let the storm come.
 
Chapter 32: The Tournament Begins
The sect had not gathered like this in years.
Lanterns swayed above the dueling platform, their flames flickering in the mountain wind. Disciples packed the surrounding terraces, their voices buzzing like a hive. Elders sat upon raised seats, their gazes heavy, while stewards kept order with sharp words and sharper glares.
