Liang met his gaze, the faintest smile tugging his lips. “I’ll stand as long as I must.”
From the shadows of the crowd, Ren Yao watched every movement, every strike. His eyes glinted, fissures faintly visible beneath his skin.
“He endures,” Ren murmured, voice sharp with disdain. “But endurance is nothing next to brilliance.”
The seed in his chest pulsed eagerly, whispering. Yes. Let him climb. The higher he rises, the harder he will fall when you break him.
Ren’s grin curved sharp as a blade.
As the sun dipped, Elder Jian rose once more. His staff struck stone, silencing the roar of the crowd.
“The first rounds end. Tomorrow, the tournament continues. Let those who remain prepare, for the eyes of the sect are upon you.”
The crowd murmured, disciples dispersing slowly, excitement still buzzing like fire.
Liang stood alone on the platform, the sparrow circling once above before perching on the railing. His body ached, blood seeped through bandages, but his breath was steady.
The sect had seen. And tomorrow, they would see more.
 
Chapter 33: Ren Yao’s Shadow
