Mei Rong saw fields stretching further than sight yet they did not stretch. They were not fields in any agricultural sense. Not grasses. Not flowering plants. Not sky mirrored in shallow waters. They were the endless unfolding of being showing itself in a way that neither required interpretation nor forbade it. She felt the whole cosmos breathing even while the concept of cosmos had already died.
Wu Sen spoke but not aloud. Speech had lost purpose. There was no one to hear. There was no one to be addressed. Yet his expression moved through the entire expanse like a perfect circle without circumference. And that expression held no content and no idea. It was the radiant silence of the Real acknowledging that nothing more was required.
The children turned to Liang. They did not look at him. Looking was gone. But being looked upon was felt. Yet not as attention. It was felt as inclusion. A recognition that separation had never been real. The children had never been younger. He had never been older. The breath did not move from generation to generation. The breath was beyond time.
Liang felt his last sorrow release. Not because sorrow was answered or healed. But because he saw with flawless certainty that sorrow had never been true. Its entire existence had been a work of misidentification. Nothing had ever been lost. Nothing had ever needed to be restored. The path had not led to truth. The path had revealed that truth had never been elsewhere.
They walked until walking itself no longer described anything at all. The next moment came without arriving. What they found had not appeared. What they saw was not newly revealed. The world was simply seen as the world before any essence had been layered upon it.
What lay ahead was a great expanse. Not wider. Not deeper. Not purer. It did not contain sacred structures nor radiant towers nor heavenly figures. It did not offer dissolution nor eternal serenity nor final reward. It offered only this.
Absolute.
Uncontainable.
Impossible to diminish.
Impossible to defend.
The children entered first. Liang and Mei Rong followed together. Wu Sen came without coming. The valley still existed. The river still existed. The cranes still existed. The breath still existed. The world did not disappear. It fulfilled itself.
At last something like a wind moved across them. But wind was no longer the element that stirs the air. It was the perfect expression of being beyond motion. It was the sound of existence reminding itself that it has always been free. And the plain that once had seemed to wait for them accepted their presence without ceremony.
No one questioned whether they had crossed into another world. No one celebrated. Celebration presupposes change. Fulfillment presupposes desire. Revelation presupposes ignorance.
There was only awareness beyond awareness.
Peace beyond peace.
Reality neither separate nor united with itself.
The breath without boundary.
And they did not vanish.
And they did not remain.
They simply were.
 
Chapter 125: The World That Could Not Be Other
