A presence awaited them.
Not person. Not deity. Not master. Not force. Not essence narrow enough to be called essence.
It neither radiated authority nor emanated welcome nor compelled reverence. It was not light. It was not thought. It was not form. It was the ground beyond ground. The life beyond life. The only possible truth of all worlds. It was everything.
And it remained motionless.
Not as a thing placed. Not as a position. Not as the object of any journey.
Its recognition of them had already been complete before they had stepped into being.
For they had never stepped into being.
They had always been being.
They approached. Not toward. Toward implies not yet.
They simply stood where standing was no different than being held.
The children stopped. Not out of hesitation. Not out of awe. Not out of reverence. They simply did not move because there was no longer any difference between motion and stillness.
Liang understood in that instant without understanding. He received without receiving. The final seed of selfhood that had persisted even as dust in a sunbeam now released itself. Not with force. Not with enlightenment. Not with transformation. It was more like water realizing it had always been ocean.
The breath filled everything.
And the breath did not fill.
The breath rose.
And the breath did not rise.
Mei Rong raised her hand.
It was the first and last gesture of the world. It was the gesture that belonged to neither beginning nor ending nor return. It was the gesture that was neither prayer nor declaration. The gesture of pure allowing.
A wind that was not wind came from everywhere at once.
Not to announce.
Not to complete.
Simply to express.
The space that was not a city began to breathe.
Yet even breathing had no rhythm.
Movement arose that was not movement.
Walls that were not walls began unfolding the infinite. Not outward. Not inward. But as the self knowing of existence that does not need witness to be known.
Wu Sen smiled.
Not in joy. Not in relief. Not in wonder.
It was the smile of absolute knowing that has never asked a question.
And then at last they saw.
If seeing still had meaning.
It was a garden.
But not like the ancients built.
Not like the mind imagines as paradise.
A garden of pure actuality. No boundary between flower and light. No boundary between fragrance and time. No boundary between death and life. No boundary between becoming and being.
It was not an end.
It was not a beginning.
It was the origin before origins.
The plain.
The valley.
The breath.
The path.
God.
The unutterable.
The nameless.
Everything.
Liang entered it by not entering.
Mei Rong breathed it by not breathing.
Wu Sen understood it by not understanding.
The children were the garden more effortlessly than water reflects the sky before sky and reflection are known.
And the world did not change.
It had always been this.
 
Chapter 127: The Garden That Waited Without Waiting
The breath did not end but it softened like a tide that had reached its furthest reach and chose not to withdraw yet chose nothing at all. Awareness did not recede. It remained in total clarity. There was no return because return belonged to direction and direction had not been born again. Liang did not open his eyes because they had never been closed yet sight awakened to a deeper intimacy. He stood at the edge of the garden though edges were mere habits of speech and not truths within this place. The stillness that filled everything was not quiet. It was the fullness before any sound is required.
The garden extended in all directions yet no direction could be walked toward for walking no longer meant what it once meant. Trees beyond naming lifted branches that were not branches for they did not terminate. Their being did not arrive at a limit. Leaves showed no pattern yet were not random for pattern and randomness are twin illusions woven from the concept of scarcity. A quiet radiance moved through them that was not light as the eyes know it and yet it revealed. Mei Rong stood beside him though beside no longer implied distance or proximity. She regarded nothing and in that non regard all things rested in unassailable wholeness.
Wu Sen was smiling. It was the kind of smile that bore no trace of reaction. It was the recognition of reality so complete that irony had lost its structure. Even delight was only a faint shadow of this presence. The children were not ahead nor behind. They were not separate nor joined. They were simply present as presence itself moving through expression. Their footsteps produced no imprint yet the garden answered their movement with a rising fragrance not of flower nor fruit but of reverberant truth. Nothing here blossomed or withered. Time was not suspended. It was fulfilled.
