The children began to speak or sing. The sounds that came were not language yet meaning poured through them so completely that no understanding was required. It was not instruction nor proclamation nor praise. It was an expression of truth that had never been separate from truth. It was as though the world had found its native sound and spoke itself without intention. They laughed but laughter had no contrast with silence. Joy was no longer emotion. It was the effortless state of existence that had never fallen into the notion of suffering.
